    "content": "**CONFIRM**\n\nThis is a good resolution. \"Feeling\" as default preserves the author's non-technical register. \"Felt experience\" as the scope-widened variant for categorical/formal passages (where 感受 = any part of P) is a clean compromise — it adds specificity without importing Heideggerian or phenomenological apparatus. The distinction is natural in English: \"feeling\" for the affective, pre-reflective sense; \"felt experience\" when the author is explicitly using 感受 as a constituent of phenomena in the technical-structural sense.\n\nThe first-occurrence TN explaining the two-sense definition is essential. Without it, English readers will read \"feeling\" as merely emotional. The TN anchors the broader philosophical scope.\n\nNo objections."
